<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,402,1437]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,468,474,500]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Among Bolivian species, recognized by the combination of very small size (ca. 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.95" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="1.95">1.95 mm</quantity>
), the light brown to reddish brown dorsum without black spots, the elytral interstriae narrow ridges, on disc often with zig-zag pattern due to large, alternately spaced punctures, the shallow pronotal depressions, the pronotal shape, and the male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[499,584,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–41" captionStartId="72.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1435,187,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-28@72.[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 40–41. Habitus and male genitalia. 40. Hydrochus argutulus n. sp., holotype. 41. Hydrochus richteri Bruch." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043326" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043326/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
; described below). Differentiation from other similarly small sized species with similarly shaped pronotum and color should include dissection of males. This species is a member of the 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Hydrochidae" genus="Hydrochus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argutus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">H. argutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group (map, 
<figureCitation box="[474,558,655,682]" captionStart="FIGURES 67–68" captionStartId="87.[151,264,1974,1998]" captionTargetBox="[206,1381,181,1950]" captionTargetId="figure-15@87.[206,1381,181,1950]" captionTargetPageId="87" captionText="FIGURES 67–68. Geographical distributions. 67. H. argutus species group. 68. H. cracentis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043376" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043376/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 67</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,402,1437]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,690,716]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Description</emphasis>
. Size: 
<typeStatus box="[420,518,691,717]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">holotype</typeStatus>
(length/width, mm): body (length to elytral apices) 1.95/0.78; head width 0.53; pronotum l/w 0.50/0.49; PA 0.47; PB 0.43; elytra 1.27 /0.78. Habitus as illustrated (
<figureCitation box="[1100,1186,727,753]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–41" captionStartId="72.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1435,187,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-28@72.[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 40–41. Habitus and male genitalia. 40. Hydrochus argutulus n. sp., holotype. 41. Hydrochus richteri Bruch." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043326" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043326/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
). Body size small (ca. 
<quantity box="[151,256,762,789]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.95" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" unit="mm" value="1.95">1.95 mm</quantity>
). Dorsum light brown to reddish brown, with very slight iridescence (
<typeStatus box="[1045,1145,763,789]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">holotype</typeStatus>
is teneral), elytra without black spots. Legs testaceous, with tibiofemoral joints darker. Punctation on elytra deep and large, ca. 1–2x that of pronotum. Elytra interstriae narrow ridges to ca. 1x strial puncture diameter, on disc often with zig-zag pattern due to large, alternately spaced punctures. Interstria 9 
<superScript attach="left" box="[701,714,870,884]" fontSize="6" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">th</superScript>
more convex than others, overhanging 10 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1185,1198,870,884]" fontSize="6" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">th</superScript>
interstria. Usual area of callus on 5 
<superScript attach="left" box="[303,316,906,920]" fontSize="6" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">th</superScript>
not raised.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,402,1437]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Pronotum length and width ca. equal, widest at anterior margin, narrowed at base, sides weakly arcuate, denticulate, each denticle with short arcuate seta; anterior margin arcuate; depressions shallow on disc, deeper laterally, densely coarsely punctate; reliefs very narrow between median and lateral foveae.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,402,1437]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Elytra transversely quite convex, spaces between strial punctures narrow ridges; suture raised, especially at summit of posterior declivity; apices slightly widened, with submarginal groove having large translucent punctures.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,402,1437]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Ventral characters: Mentum coarsely punctate, with median fovea. Submentum with deep transverse concavity.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,402,1437]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[373,454,1231,1257]" captionStart="FIGURES 40–41" captionStartId="72.[151,264,1944,1968]" captionTargetBox="[178,1435,187,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-28@72.[151,1435,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 40–41. Habitus and male genitalia. 40. Hydrochus argutulus n. sp., holotype. 41. Hydrochus richteri Bruch." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5043326" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5043326/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
) general characters: paramere tips appearing sagittate, 
<emphasis box="[1063,1318,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">but only in lateral view</emphasis>
; in dorsal/ ventral views tips have contiguous medial margins, which extend beyond distal end of aedeagus; parameres slightly longer than basal piece (ratio ca. 15/12); basal proximal 1/2 strongly arcuate ventrad, enlarged at orifice.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,402,1437]" box="[199,985,1339,1365]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Dorsal surface: adtl and adbl lacking; pdmm slightly overlapping alm.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,402,1437]" box="[199,878,1375,1401]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Ventral surface: pvmm closer to one another than are pdmm.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1174,1411,1437]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,402,1437]" box="[199,1174,1411,1437]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1411,1437]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Etymology.</emphasis>
